405
00:27:59,344 --> 00:28:01,209
-Really?
-Yeah.

406
00:28:04,382 --> 00:28:07,146
I want to recommend you to Enzo.

407
00:28:07,218 --> 00:28:08,276
Me?

408
00:28:08,353 --> 00:28:10,583
I think
you should finish the film.

409
00:28:12,090 --> 00:28:15,582
I know you can do a good job.
You're a talented kid.

410
00:28:15,660 --> 00:28:17,628
You have helped
the picture a lot.

411
00:28:17,696 --> 00:28:18,958
I have seen that...

412
00:28:19,030 --> 00:28:20,725
in the second unit shots
I have gotten.

413
00:28:31,209 --> 00:28:34,701
The footage
of the cosmic rays...

414
00:28:34,779 --> 00:28:37,304
that was your idea.

415
00:28:37,382 --> 00:28:39,350
It's a good idea.

416
00:28:42,687 --> 00:28:43,984
We talk to him tomorrow.

417
00:28:53,431 --> 00:28:55,262
It is sonic boom
of the Concorde.

418
00:28:55,333 --> 00:28:58,427
It's so fucking amazing.
We're living in the future, man.

419
00:28:59,471 --> 00:29:01,496
...acting is to the scenario.

420
00:29:01,573 --> 00:29:03,200
I found this great place
in St. Germain.

421
00:29:03,274 --> 00:29:05,174
Would you excuse me one second?

422
00:29:05,243 --> 00:29:07,211
I've got some big news.

423
00:29:07,278 --> 00:29:10,839
Can't you see I'm talking
to someone right now?

424
00:29:10,915 --> 00:29:12,314
Give me two minutes.

425
00:29:12,383 --> 00:29:14,544
Excuse me,
you were saying?

426
00:29:14,619 --> 00:29:16,484
It's called
theater of revolution.

427
00:29:16,554 --> 00:29:19,717
It's going to be a movement,
a voice, a poetry workshop.

428
00:29:19,791 --> 00:29:21,588
I'm sure you'd love this place.

429
00:29:21,659 --> 00:29:25,060
-Did you hear about poor Felix?
-I hope he's OK.

430
00:29:25,130 --> 00:29:26,722
He's so talented.

431
00:29:26,798 --> 00:29:28,959
Working with him
is so much fun.

432
00:29:29,033 --> 00:29:31,058
I remember once,
when we finished early...

433
00:29:31,136 --> 00:29:32,899
and he took us all
to the go-kart ride.

434
00:29:32,971 --> 00:29:35,804
Oh, God! Come here.

435
00:29:35,874 --> 00:29:39,139
-That nobody can deny...
-Hey, babe!

436
00:29:39,210 --> 00:29:43,476
For he's a jolly good fellow

437
00:29:43,548 --> 00:29:45,243
For he's a jolly good fellow

438
00:29:45,316 --> 00:29:47,750
It's Felix DeMarco!

439
00:29:47,819 --> 00:29:49,548
That nobody can deny

440
00:29:49,621 --> 00:29:51,248
That nobody can deny

441
00:29:51,322 --> 00:29:54,120
Thank you. Thank you.
So kind.

442
00:29:55,160 --> 00:29:57,025
Ladies and gentlemen...

443
00:29:57,095 --> 00:29:59,928
I'd like
to make an announcement.

444
00:29:59,998 --> 00:30:01,295
I'm sure
you've probably heard...

445
00:30:01,366 --> 00:30:03,527
about the mad events
of this evening...

446
00:30:03,601 --> 00:30:05,660
but we're OK, right?

447
00:30:05,737 --> 00:30:10,197
But there's one more thing
that happened.

448
00:30:14,879 --> 00:30:16,904
I asked Brigit to marry me...

449
00:30:16,981 --> 00:30:19,711
and she said yes!

450
00:30:19,784 --> 00:30:23,117
And so, we can't wait
one moment further...

451
00:30:23,188 --> 00:30:25,622
and we're
setting sail tomorrow.

452
00:30:33,798 --> 00:30:37,029
Don't stand around
staring at us!

453
00:30:37,101 --> 00:30:38,466
Let's dance!

454
00:30:54,619 --> 00:30:56,314
Dad. Dad.

455
00:30:56,387 --> 00:30:58,753
Hey, you all right?

456
00:30:58,823 --> 00:31:02,054
Yeah. I misplaced my glasses
on the plane.

457
00:31:02,126 --> 00:31:04,219
Thank you very much.

458
00:31:04,295 --> 00:31:05,922
Let me hold your hand.

459
00:31:14,272 --> 00:31:16,069
Hold on. Wait.

460
00:31:18,276 --> 00:31:21,370
I took a sleeping pill,
and I ate all the ice cream.

461
00:31:23,348 --> 00:31:25,213
It's good to see you.

462
00:31:25,283 --> 00:31:28,184
Good to see you at Christmas,
even briefly.

463
00:31:28,253 --> 00:31:31,051
Wait a second.
I brought you something.

464
00:31:34,692 --> 00:31:35,852
Thanks, Dad.

465
00:31:37,228 --> 00:31:40,629
I had a dream the other night...

466
00:31:40,698 --> 00:31:42,188
and I thought of you.

467
00:31:42,267 --> 00:31:45,202
Well, you were in it.

468
00:31:45,270 --> 00:31:47,170
I was watching these...

469
00:31:47,238 --> 00:31:51,368
hideous films of Vietnam
on the television.

470
00:31:51,442 --> 00:31:55,538
And I had
this deep, desultory dream...

471
00:31:55,613 --> 00:31:59,344
where I met a son
that I didn't know I had.

472
00:32:01,252 --> 00:32:03,550
And he looked like you.

473
00:32:03,621 --> 00:32:07,250
You were there, too.
Two brothers.

474
00:32:07,325 --> 00:32:12,058
But then I realized that
he was a soldier in the war.

475
00:32:12,130 --> 00:32:15,258
And when I woke up,
I had these...

476
00:32:15,333 --> 00:32:20,396
these feelings
of worry and of loss.

477
00:32:20,471 --> 00:32:22,234
And I wondered...

478
00:32:22,307 --> 00:32:25,071
this is curious...

479
00:32:25,143 --> 00:32:27,008
could I have had a child
by another woman...

480
00:32:27,078 --> 00:32:29,239
and never known about it?

481
00:32:29,314 --> 00:32:31,782
Isn't that a curious thought?

482
00:32:34,152 --> 00:32:37,781
I think about it
sometimes and...

483
00:32:37,855 --> 00:32:40,551
What if I met a boy
and he looked like you?

484
00:32:42,260 --> 00:32:44,558
Maybe it's really my son.

485
00:32:47,131 --> 00:32:50,396
Sometimes I'll be driving
down the street...

486
00:32:50,468 --> 00:32:52,026
and I'll see someone
who looks familiar...

487
00:32:52,103 --> 00:32:54,230
like it could be my brother.

488
00:32:54,305 --> 00:32:56,296
You know?

489
00:32:56,374 --> 00:32:58,274
So, maybe it's true, Dad.

490
00:32:59,577 --> 00:33:02,637
It is possible, Paul.

491
00:33:02,714 --> 00:33:06,013
I wasn't always faithful
to your mother.

492
00:33:09,787 --> 00:33:11,118
When I was your age...

493
00:33:11,189 --> 00:33:13,419
all I could think about
was women.

494
00:33:13,491 --> 00:33:15,857
It was like a disease
or a curse.

495
00:33:17,528 --> 00:33:20,122
I think I know
what you mean, Dad.

496
00:33:34,645 --> 00:33:36,545
Kids are nice.

497
00:33:38,282 --> 00:33:40,648
When do you think
you'll have some of your own?

498
00:33:42,020 --> 00:33:44,079
I don't know, Dad.

499
00:33:46,124 --> 00:33:49,059
Have you thought about
coming back home?

500
00:33:49,127 --> 00:33:50,822
Your mother wanted me
to ask you.

501
00:33:50,895 --> 00:33:52,419
I don't know.

502
00:33:52,497 --> 00:33:55,466
Excuse me.
We found your glasses.

503
00:33:55,533 --> 00:33:57,467
Oh, thank you.

504
00:33:57,535 --> 00:33:59,503
Thank you very much.

505
00:33:59,570 --> 00:34:00,764
Wow.

506
00:34:07,512 --> 00:34:10,447
I think it's time to go.

507
00:34:13,217 --> 00:34:15,185
I'm very glad for you, Paul.

508
00:34:15,253 --> 00:34:17,915
I know you'll do well
in this new job of yours.

509
00:34:17,989 --> 00:34:19,547
What is it?

510
00:34:19,624 --> 00:34:21,353
It's a science-fiction film...

511
00:34:21,426 --> 00:34:25,157
about a futuristic spy
named Dragonfly.

512
00:34:25,229 --> 00:34:27,288
That's interesting.

513
00:34:27,365 --> 00:34:29,697
Your grandmother
used to call dragonflies...

514
00:34:29,767 --> 00:34:31,564
the Devil's darning needles.

515
00:34:31,636 --> 00:34:32,967
She told me that
they come in the night...

516
00:34:33,037 --> 00:34:34,902
and stitch up your mouth
if you use profanity...

517
00:34:34,972 --> 00:34:36,530
or were otherwise voluble.

518
00:34:36,607 --> 00:34:38,131
This isn't exactly about that.

519
00:34:38,209 --> 00:34:40,643
Maybe you can use it somehow.

